{"parentUuid":"4ca12cb7-a71a-4a96-a874-df64c1f26ce7","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/ryan/formal-conjectures","sessionId":"9b70b198-db63-4160-a7e6-30a24e50d625","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"ai-erdos-7","agentId":"a022a41ea63caf011","slug":"cached-twirling-pascal","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TFS378XduE6fCWEQLz6Swy","type":"tool_result","content":"# Erdős Problem #969\n\n**Status:** OPEN\n\n**Problem Statement:**\n\nLet Q(x) count the number of squarefree integers in [1,x]. Determine the order of magnitude in the error term in the asymptotic:\n\nQ(x) = (6/π²)x + E(x)\n\n**Tags:** number theory\n\n**Key Results:**\n\nThe problem addresses bounds on the error term E(x):\n\n- Elementary methods establish \"E(x) ≪ x^(1/2)\"\n- The prime number theorem implies the error is \"o(x^(1/2))\"\n- Best unconditional bound: \"x^(1/2-o(1))\" (Walfisz)\n- Lower bound: \"E(x) ≫ x^(1/4)\" (Evelyn and Linfoot)\n- Riemann Hypothesis would follow from \"E(x) ≪ x^(1/4)\"\n- Conditional on Riemann Hypothesis, best known: \"x^(11/35+o(1))\" (Liu)\n\n**Important Note:**\n\nThe true order of magnitude remains unknown even under the Riemann Hypothesis.\n\n**Related Resources:**\n\n- Original sources: Erdős [Er65b], [Er81h, p.176]\n- OEIS sequence: A013928\n- References: Walfisz [Wa63], Evelyn and Linfoot [EvLi31], Liu [Li16]"}]},"uuid":"65f9e715-6d0f-44c0-9da7-5ec5dd91c229","timestamp":"2026-03-11T08:01:33.200Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"4ca12cb7-a71a-4a96-a874-df64c1f26ce7"}
{"parentUuid":"65f9e715-6d0f-44c0-9da7-5ec5dd91c229","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/ryan/formal-conjectures","sessionId":"9b70b198-db63-4160-a7e6-30a24e50d625","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"ai-erdos-7","agentId":"a022a41ea63caf011","slug":"cached-twirling-pascal","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01KaPm1J39xFLRXMWGuxVUtQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is the full content retrieved from **https://www.erdosproblems.com/969**:\n\n---\n\n**Erdos Problem #969** -- Status: OPEN\n\n**Problem Statement:**\n\nLet Q(x) count the number of squarefree integers in [1, x]. Determine the order of magnitude in the error term in the asymptotic:\n\nQ(x) = (6/pi^2)x + E(x)\n\n**Tags:** Number theory\n\n**Key Results / Notes:**\n\n- Elementary methods establish E(x) << x^(1/2).\n- The prime number theorem implies the error is o(x^(1/2)).\n- Best unconditional bound: x^(1/2 - o(1)) (Walfisz).\n- Lower bound: E(x) >> x^(1/4) (Evelyn and Linfoot).\n- The Riemann Hypothesis would follow from E(x) << x^(1/4).\n- Conditional on the Riemann Hypothesis, the best known bound is x^(11/35 + o(1)) (Liu).\n\nThe true order of magnitude remains unknown even under the Riemann Hypothesis.\n\n**Citations / References:**\n\n- Erdos [Er65b], [Er81h, p.176]\n- Walfisz [Wa63]\n- Evelyn and Linfoot [EvLi31]\n- Liu [Li16]\n- OEIS sequence: A013928"}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":482,"cache_read_input_tokens":15939,"output_tokens":347,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":482},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CYvwbAzHN3TsdTnQJHF1u","type":"assistant","uuid":"9308c296-ea8a-4829-a820-cbef9a037478","timestamp":"2026-03-11T08:01:38.436Z"}
